  "prompt": "What are the best small classes for freshmen at Southern Connecticut State?",
  "response": "Southern Connecticut State University (SCSU) offers a variety of small classes that can be a great fit for freshmen, allowing for more personalized attention and a chance to build relationships with professors and peers. The \"best\" classes can vary depending on your interests, major, and academic goals, but here are some general recommendations for small classes that are often popular with first-year students:\n\n### 1. **First-Year Seminars (FYS)**  \n   - These are specifically designed for freshmen and often focus on interesting, interdisciplinary topics. Class sizes are intentionally kept small to encourage discussion and engagement.  \n   - Examples:  \n     - FYS 100: First-Year Seminar (various topics)  \n     - FYS 101: First-Year Seminar with a focus on critical thinking, writing, and research skills.\n\n### 2. **Introduction to Liberal Arts (LAR 100)**  \n   - This course helps students explore the liberal arts and sciences, often with a small class size. It\u2019s a great way to get acclimated to college-level thinking and writing.\n\n### 3. **Introductory Psychology (PSY 100)**  \n   - Taught in smaller sections, this course is a popular choice for students interested in psychology or those fulfilling general education requirements.\n\n### 4. **Introductory Sociology (SOC 100)**  \n   - Another social science course with smaller class sizes, perfect for students curious about societal structures and behaviors.\n\n### 5. **Public Speaking (COM 163)**  \n   - This course is often small and interactive, helping students build confidence and communication skills that are useful in any major.\n\n### 6. **Creative Writing (ENG 228)**  \n   - If you enjoy writing, this small, hands-on class can be a great way to explore your creativity while improving your writing skills.\n\n### 7. **Introduction to Philosophy (PHL 101)**  \n   - This course often has smaller sections and introduces students to critical thinking and philosophical concepts.\n\n### 8. **Health and Wellness (HEA 110)**  \n   - A smaller class that focuses on personal health, wellness, and lifestyle choices, which can be helpful for adjusting to college life.\n\n### 9. **Human Biology (BIO 100)**  \n   - For students interested in science, this course is often taught in smaller sections and provides a good foundation for further study in biology or health-related fields.\n\n### 10. **Art or Music Appreciation (ART 101, MUS 100)**  \n   - These courses are often smaller and provide a creative outlet while fulfilling general education requirements.\n\n### Tips for Finding Small Classes:  \n   - Check the class size when registering via Banner.  \n   - Consult with your academic advisor to identify courses that fit your interests and goals.  \n   - Consider taking a seminar or special topics course, as these are often smaller and more interactive.  \n\nUltimately, the best small classes for you will depend on your academic interests and major. Be sure to explore the course catalog and talk to your advisor for personalized recommendations!",
